window.REVIEW = {"brand": {"score": 8.4, "headline": "A genuinely premium, cohesive \"Celestial Atelier\" that leaves Keen/Kasamba looking cheap — held back mainly by a primary CTA that doesn't yet physically stand off its own animated cosmos.", "summary": "The design system is disciplined and convincingly luxury: the violet-void + champagne-gold palette, Cormorant/Jost pairing, heritage \"since 1989\" framing, and restrained signature moments (seal breathing at a 1.045 scale, gold-sweep on editorial italics, correctly-used glassmorphism on the scrolled header, hero card, and dropdowns) read as a heritage house, not a transactional directory. That alone puts it a tier above competitors. The biggest opportunity is conversion-facing craft rather than taste: the primary \"Get Your Reading\" button is, at rest, a flat gold rectangle whose only depth appears on hover, so against the busy animated starfield it can merge into the field instead of commanding it — and the \"breathing glow + material top highlight\" the brief believes is shipped is not actually bound to the button. Secondary opportunities cluster around motion settling, an off-palette green availability indicator, and carrying the standardized CTA verb and $1/min risk-reversal onto the 190-card advisors page, which is the highest-intent surface and currently the least reinforced.", "strengths": ["Palette and type system are cohesive and authentically premium — champagne-gold on violet-void with Cormorant/Jost decisively out-classes the flat, transactional look of Keen/Kasamba.", "Real motion restraint where it counts: seal medallion breathes at only 1.045 scale / .5-.85 opacity, gold-sweep is reserved for editorial italics, and prefers-reduced-motion is respected across 7+ blocks — evidence of craft, not just effects.", "Glassmorphism is used correctly and sparingly (scrolled-header blur+saturate, hero-card backdrop-blur, dropdown panels) rather than smeared across everything.", "Social proof is well-marshalled (35 years, 10M+ readings, 270K 5-star, 4.9/5, <1-in-20 accepted) and the risk-reversal is surfaced near CTAs.", "Heritage 'since 1989' narrative and the compass-star / source-seal language give the brand a defensible, ownable world competitors can't cheaply copy."], "findings": [{"area": "CTA prominence / material depth", "observation": "The primary .btn-primary is a flat gold gradient (2px radius) with box-shadow only on :hover; there is no resting shadow, no outer glow, and no material top highlight. The 'subtle breathing gold glow + material top highlight' the brief assumes is live is not actually attached to the button (the 'breathe' keyframe is unused on home, 'goldSweep' drives text, no ::before exists). Against the drifting glows, ~1500 twinkling stars, and grain, the resting CTA can read flat and blend into the field.", "recommendation": "Give the CTA a resting physical presence: a soft outer drop-shadow plus a low-opacity blurred gold halo BEHIND the button (not on the fill), a 1px inset ivory top highlight via ::before for a 'pressable' material edge, and a very slow low-amplitude breathing glow on that halo only (~4-6s, opacity ~.85-1). Keep the 2px radius and gradient. This is the single highest-leverage conversion change.", "priority": "high"}, {"area": "Primary CTA destination", "observation": "The hero 'Get Your Reading' links to #offer (an in-page scroll), not into the psychics list or a start-reading flow, while the conversion goal is a first paid reading.", "recommendation": "Point the primary CTA at the highest-intent next step (advisors grid or a start flow) and demote the scroll-to-offer to the secondary link. Preserve the reassurance microcopy on the new target.", "priority": "high"}, {"area": "Advisors grid — verb + risk reversal", "observation": "The 190-card advisors page (highest purchase intent on the site) uses per-card 'Connect →' and does not carry the standardized 'Get Your Reading' verb or the '$1/min · Satisfaction guaranteed' reassurance that appears elsewhere.", "recommendation": "Standardize the card CTA verb and surface the $1/min risk-reversal at least once above the grid and in a sticky footer bar, so the most decision-heavy page reinforces the same promise as the hero.", "priority": "med"}, {"area": "Off-palette availability indicator", "observation": "'Available now' status uses a pulsing saturated green (#7BD389, 5 instances) with a glowing dot — a generic SaaS/presence-indicator cue that breaks the champagne-gold/violet heritage world.", "recommendation": "Recolor the available state to a warm gold or muted sage with a soft ivory glow, and reserve the pulse strictly for genuinely-live availability so it reads as a considered brand signal rather than a system light.", "priority": "med"}, {"area": "Motion density / stillness", "observation": "~22 always-on infinite animations; a single viewport can stack cosmic drift, ~1500 twinkling stars, grain, gold text-sweep, seal breathing, and node pulses. The page can feel perpetually shimmering, which undercuts luxury calm and may feel restless to readers arriving in grief or crisis.", "recommendation": "Cap simultaneous motion per viewport, let the hero fully settle after its entrance, slow the twinkle further, and let stillness/whitespace carry the premium tone. Reduced-motion is already respected — extend that same restraint to the default state.", "priority": "med"}, {"area": "Small-text legibility for the demographic", "observation": "Heavy reliance on 10-12px uppercase gold labels with .18em tracking on a dark ground (14 instances at 11px, 15 at 12px); reassurance microcopy sits at 12.5px in base gold. For an audience skewing 30-65, gold-on-dark at 10-11px is low-comfort.", "recommendation": "Set a 12px floor for body-adjacent labels, lift key microcopy to ~13px, and brighten the reassurance line near CTAs to gold-bright rather than base gold for contrast.", "priority": "med"}, {"area": "Reassurance hierarchy near CTA", "observation": "The hero lead already states 'New members from $1/min' and the cta-micro 20px below repeats 'Your first reading from $1/min · Satisfaction guaranteed' — two stacked price mentions taxing the same glance.", "recommendation": "Split the roles: let one line carry price and the other carry the guarantee, and render the satisfaction line as a discrete hairline-gold 'seal chip' (subtle glass) so the guarantee gains material weight and echoes the source-seal medallion language.", "priority": "low"}], "motion_notes": "Restraint is mostly good and clearly intentional — seal/aura breathing are low-amplitude, the gold sweep is confined to editorial italics, and prefers-reduced-motion is honored across the site. The risk is cumulative, not per-effect: ~22 concurrent infinite loops mean the composition never fully rests, and a luxury house earns its premium as much from stillness as from shimmer. Guidance: motion should either guide the eye to an action (this is where a slow breathing halo on the CTA earns its place) or reward a scroll beat, not run everywhere at once. Prune background twinkle/drift/grain from any viewport that also contains an active accent animation, and treat the settle-to-stillness after the hero entrance as a feature. Pulsing green presence dots and stacked ambient loops are the two places motion currently tips from atmosphere toward gimmick.", "risks": ["The intended CTA glow/highlight is believed shipped but isn't bound to the button — the team may be optimizing copy while the primary conversion element is quietly under-powered against its own background.", "Perpetual ambient motion can read as restless rather than serene to a vulnerable audience (grief, major decisions), subtly contradicting the 'trusted, calm guidance' brand promise.", "Off-palette green availability dots and any residual 'Connect'/'advisor' terminology leak a transactional, tech-directory feel that is exactly the competitor aesthetic this redesign is trying to escape.", "Dense small gold-on-dark labels risk legibility complaints and a faintly 'designed for young eyes' feel for a 30-65 core audience.", "High animation count plus large per-page cinematic hero imagery is a performance/CLS risk on mid-range mobile, where a janky luxury site reads as less premium than a fast simple one."]}, "cro": {"findings": [{"element": "Persistent floating CTA (.float-cta, bottom-right pill, appears on scroll)", "issue": "The always-visible conversion path is the LOWEST-contrast button on the page: a translucent violet glass pill (rgba(34,24,84,.8)) with ivory text and a thin gold hairline border. It does not use the gold fill that marks the primary action. The one CTA a user can always reach reads as tertiary chrome, and its label 'Get a reading, from $1/min' also breaks the standardized wording.", "fix": "Rebuild the float CTA with the same gold gradient fill + ink text as .btn-primary (keep the rounded pill shape), and relabel to 'Get Your Reading · $1/min'. It should be the single most prominent thing on screen while scrolling.", "impact": "High. The persistent CTA is the most-seen conversion control; making it the highest-contrast element (salience / Von Restorff) directly lifts click-through on every scroll depth.", "effort": "low"}, {"element": "CTA label consistency across the funnel", "issue": "The brief claims 'Get Your Reading' is standardized sitewide, but the build shows four different labels for the same action: hero/nav 'Get Your Reading', float pill 'Get a reading, from $1/min', psychic cards 'Connect →', and the advisors hero 'Find A Psychic'. Inconsistent verbs force the user to re-learn the action at each step and dilute the trained click.", "fix": "Standardize the action verb to 'Get Your Reading' everywhere. Cards can append price ('Get Your Reading · $1/min') but must share the verb; retire 'Connect', 'Find A Psychic' as primary-button labels.", "impact": "Med. A single repeated CTA phrase compounds recognition and reduces micro-hesitation at each decision point.", "effort": "low"}, {"element": "Psychic card CTA on advisors.html (190-card grid, per-card 'Connect →' text link)", "issue": "The reading actually starts from a card, yet the card's CTA is the weakest visual element on it (a small arrow text link), while 190 cards each present a full micro-decision (photo, tagline, rating, price, availability). This is classic choice overload (Hick's Law) with no visual funnel to a next action.", "fix": "Turn the card CTA into a small filled-gold button; default-sort to 'Available now'; cap the initial visible set (e.g. 12–24 with 'Show more') or add a 'Best match / talk now' express path so users aren't forced to evaluate the full grid before converting.", "impact": "High. Reducing the decision set and strengthening the card-level CTA attacks the biggest drop-off point between browse and first paid reading.", "effort": "med"}, {"element": "Above-the-fold offer + risk reversal on home hero", "issue": "The concrete $1/min offer block and the breathing 'source seal' 100% guarantee medallion live in section 2, below the first viewport. The hero carries only microcopy ('New members from $1/min · Satisfaction guaranteed'); the visual risk-reversal cue the design invested in is not seen at the moment of the first CTA.", "fix": "Place a compact guarantee badge (small source-seal + 'Satisfaction guaranteed') directly adjacent to the hero primary button so price anchor and risk reversal are visible together at the point of decision.", "impact": "Med. Co-locating offer + guarantee with the CTA lowers perceived risk exactly when the user weighs the first click.", "effort": "low"}, {"element": "Motion salience vs the primary CTA", "issue": "Ambient motion is everywhere near the fold (drifting cosmic glows, twinkling stars, spinning tarot, logo pulse, breathing seal), but the primary gold button has NO resting animation — only a hover transition (translateY + shadow). The brief says buttons carry a 'breathing gold glow'; the shipped CSS shows no such keyframe on .btn-primary. So every animated element competes for the eye except the action itself.", "fix": "Add a subtle, slow breathing glow (box-shadow pulse, ~4–6s) to the hero primary button and the float CTA so the single most animated element near the fold is the conversion control. Keep it gentle to preserve the luxury tone.", "impact": "Med. Aligning motion-as-attention with the action (instead of decoration) pulls the eye to the CTA in a visually busy field.", "effort": "low"}, {"element": "Mobile persistent CTA (<=980px)", "issue": "On mobile the header CTA is hidden (nav.main,.nav-cta,.util-bar{display:none}) and replaced by a burger, so the only persistent CTA is the low-contrast glass float pill that fades in on scroll. For a women-30–65 psychic audience (mobile-heavy), the strongest always-on conversion control is absent on the most important device.", "fix": "Add a full-width sticky bottom bar on mobile with a gold-filled 'Get Your Reading' + '$1/min' that is present from load (not scroll-gated), safe-area padded above the home indicator.", "impact": "High. A persistent, high-contrast mobile CTA is one of the most reliable mobile conversion levers and this device segment likely dominates traffic.", "effort": "med"}, {"element": "CTA button sizing / type (.btn-primary 13px, .nav-cta 12px, uppercase, .18em tracking)", "issue": "The primary buttons use small uppercase type with heavy letter-spacing, which shrinks perceived button size and tap legibility relative to the button's importance. The action is physically one of the smaller interactive targets on a very large-scale hero (H1 up to 94px).", "fix": "Increase primary CTA type to ~15–16px and add padding so the button reads as a deliberate focal element; keep the elegant tracking but not at the cost of size. Ensure >=44px tap height on mobile.", "impact": "Low-Med. Larger, more legible primary targets modestly improve click-through and mobile tap success.", "effort": "low"}, {"element": "Hero CTA hierarchy (STRENGTH to preserve)", "issue": "This is working well and should not be flattened: the hero pairs one gold-filled primary ('Get Your Reading') with a subordinate text-link secondary ('Meet the psychics →'), and the primary uses a strong gold-gradient fill on dark ink text — high contrast, clear single focal action. The 3-stat social-proof row (35 years / 10M+ / 270K 5★) is well placed.", "fix": "Keep this pattern. Do not add a second gold button to the hero; carry this exact primary/secondary weighting to interior heroes (advisors, readings, love, tarot) where labels currently drift.", "impact": "Med. Preserving one-primary-per-view hierarchy is what makes the rest of the funnel legible; replicate rather than dilute it.", "effort": "low"}], "predicted_lift": "Directional, no invented numbers. The redesign already wins the two hardest visual-CRO battles most competitors lose: the hero has a clean one-primary hierarchy (gold-filled 'Get Your Reading' + subordinate text link) and the primary button's color contrast is genuinely strong (gold gradient on ink). Trust cues (35 years, 10M+ readings, 270K 5★, 2% acceptance, guarantee) are present and credible. So the lift is not in the hero's first impression — it's in the persistence and repetition layer, which is where luxury sites quietly leak conversions. The three highest-probability levers, in order: (1) Make the persistent/floating CTA the highest-contrast element instead of the lowest — right now the one button a user can always reach is a translucent glass pill, which inverts the salience principle; giving it the gold fill should lift scroll-depth click-through the most for the least effort. (2) Add a real mobile sticky gold CTA present from load — for a mobile-heavy women-30–65 audience, the current scroll-gated low-contrast pill is the weakest link on the most-used device, and a persistent bottom bar is among the most reliable mobile conversion patterns known. (3) Standardize the CTA verb and strengthen the per-card button on the 190-psychic grid — the reading literally starts from a card, yet 'Connect →' is the weakest element on it while 190 full micro-decisions create choice overload (Hick's Law); a filled card CTA plus availability-first sort and a capped initial set attacks the browse-to-first-reading drop-off directly. Secondary polish (breathing glow ON the CTA rather than only on decoration, hero-adjacent guarantee badge, larger button type) compounds by aligning motion-as-attention and risk-reversal with the exact moment of decision. Net: expect the meaningful gains from persistence, consistency, and grid friction — not from touching the hero, which is already close to right. The honest risk is over-animating: this audience and price point reward calm, so every glow added to a CTA must stay slow and singular or it will read as the cheap, transactional competitors this brand is defined against.", "headline": "Premium and credible up top, but the persistent, repeated, and mobile CTAs — where conversions actually compound — are the weakest-contrast, least-consistent elements on the page.", "quick_wins": ["Give the floating/persistent CTA the gold fill (it's currently the lowest-contrast button on the page) so the always-visible action is the most prominent.", "Standardize every primary button to 'Get Your Reading' — kill the 'Connect →', 'Find A Psychic', and 'Get a reading, from $1/min' variants.", "Add a full-width sticky gold CTA bar on mobile, present from load — the mobile header CTA is currently hidden and only a faint scroll-in pill remains.", "Add a slow breathing glow to the hero primary + float CTA so the one animated thing near the fold is the action, not the decorative stars/tarot/seal.", "Pull a compact guarantee badge next to the hero button so price anchor + risk reversal are seen together at the point of the first click."], "score": 7, "summary": "The Celestial Atelier redesign nails the premium first impression: the home hero has a disciplined one-primary hierarchy (gold-filled 'Get Your Reading' with a subordinate 'Meet the psychics →' text link), the primary button uses a genuinely high-contrast gold gradient on ink text, and strong trust cues sit above the fold. That top-of-funnel is close to right and should be preserved, not touched. The conversion leakage is in the persistence and repetition layer. The always-on floating CTA is the single lowest-contrast button on the page (a translucent violet glass pill), inverting the salience principle for the control users reach most; the CTA label is not actually standardized (four different verbs across hero, float, cards, and advisors hero); the 190-psychic grid — where readings actually start — pairs choice overload with the weakest possible per-card CTA ('Connect →' text link); and on mobile the header CTA is hidden while only the faint scroll-gated pill remains, weakening the exact device this audience uses most. Motion also works against conversion: ambient stars, spinning tarot, and a breathing seal all animate, but the primary button has no resting motion (the brief's claimed 'breathing gold glow' isn't in the shipped CSS), so the eye is drawn to decoration rather than the action. None of these are hero problems — they're persistence, consistency, and grid-friction problems, which is exactly where a luxury site quietly loses first paid readings."}, "cto": {"recommendation": "Conditional Go", "headline": "Adopt it as a design system and CRO reference, not as a lift-and-shift replacement for the production site.", "summary": "This is an excellent, cohesive luxury front-end prototype — the \"Celestial Atelier\" system genuinely differentiates from the cheap-and-transactional competitors (Keen, Kasamba) and the CRO pass (standardized \"Get Your Reading\" CTA, risk-reversal near CTAs, benefit-led H1, quantified social proof) is directionally sound and worth shipping. But it is a hand-authored static HTML/CSS/JS site on GitHub Pages with roughly a dozen-plus flat pages and 190 psychic profiles baked into markup. psychicsource.com is a 35-year-old transactional business whose actual product is the plumbing this prototype does not have: real-time psychic availability/presence, per-minute telephony + billing, payment processing, accounts/auth, a CMS for 190+ constantly-changing profiles and rates, SEO/redirect equity accumulated since 1989, analytics/experimentation, PCI/accessibility/age-gating compliance, and localization. The visible \"Available now\" dots, $1/min pricing, and 3-step account flow are decorative in the prototype — they are the hardest 80% of the real system. Treating this as a site you can \"swap in\" would replace a working revenue engine with a beautiful brochure and take the business offline. The right move is to harvest the design system, component library, hero concepts, and conversion copy, and re-implement them on top of (or inside) the existing production stack/CMS/theme — a reskin and CRO uplift, not a migration. Value is very high; the framing of \"adopt to replace\" is the trap.", "migration_risks": [{"risk": "Static prototype has no backend: live availability, per-minute telephony/billing, payments, and accounts are hardcoded UI, not integrated systems. 'Replacing' the live site would remove the actual revenue-generating machinery.", "severity": "high", "mitigation": "Reframe scope to a reskin/theme layer over the existing production backend and CMS. Do not decommission any live system; port the visual system into the current stack behind the same data and checkout flows."}, {"risk": "190+ psychic profiles are baked into static HTML. Psychic rosters, rates, statuses, and availability change constantly; a hardcoded grid goes stale within hours and cannot reflect who is actually online.", "severity": "high", "mitigation": "Rebuild the advisor grid and profile pages as CMS/API-driven templates. Use the prototype's card and grid design as the presentation layer only; bind it to the live roster/presence feed."}, {"risk": "SEO and redirect equity: psychicsource.com ranks and converts on 35 years of accumulated URLs, canonical structure, and backlinks. A new static IA with different paths and no redirect/canonical strategy risks a major organic traffic and revenue drop.", "severity": "high", "mitigation": "Preserve existing URL structure or build a complete 301 redirect map, canonical tags, structured data, sitemaps, and parity of on-page SEO before any cutover. Migrate behind a staged rollout with SEO monitoring, never a hard swap."}, {"risk": "Compliance and legal surface untouched: PCI-DSS for payments, 18+ age gating, accessibility (WCAG/ADA — litigation-prone for a consumer brand), privacy/consent, and per-jurisdiction disclaimers for psychic/advice services.", "severity": "high", "mitigation": "Keep payment/PII flows in the existing PCI-compliant systems. Run an accessibility audit on the new design (cosmic gradients, gold-on-violet contrast, heavy animation, and twinkling-star motion are contrast/motion-sensitivity risks) and add prefers-reduced-motion, focus states, and semantic markup before launch."}, {"risk": "Performance and device reality: per-page cinematic hero images, ~1500 animated stars, 3D spinning tarot cards, and constant background animation are heavy on mid-range mobile — the exact device profile of the 30–65 women target audience. Slow LCP hurts both conversion and SEO.", "severity": "med", "mitigation": "Budget performance: lazy-load/compress hero art, cap or gate the star field and 3D card animations behind capability/reduced-motion checks, measure Core Web Vitals on real mid-tier mobile before adopting any effect."}, {"risk": "No analytics, experimentation, or event instrumentation. The CRO copy pass is a hypothesis; without measurement you cannot prove the new design lifts first-paid-reading conversion and could ship a regression blind.", "severity": "med", "mitigation": "Instrument the redesign and roll it out as an A/B test against the current site on the primary conversion (first paid reading), not a full replacement, so the premium bet is validated with revenue data."}, {"risk": "Maintainability: hand-authored static HTML with duplicated headers/footers/CTAs across ~15 pages has no templating or single source of truth. Editorial and rate/roster changes require touching many files by hand.", "severity": "med", "mitigation": "Convert to the production templating/CMS system (components, partials, tokens) rather than maintaining flat files. Extract the design into reusable tokens/components as the deliverable."}, {"risk": "Localization/i18n absent. If the business serves multiple locales/currencies, hardcoded English copy and USD pricing block international operation.", "severity": "low", "mitigation": "Externalize strings and pricing into the existing localization pipeline during re-implementation."}], "ongoing_ops": ["Roster/rate/availability content must flow from the CMS and presence system, not be hand-edited in HTML — the prototype's static grid is not operable day-to-day.", "Design system needs an owner: tokenize the palette (violet-indigo/champagne gold), Cormorant Garamond + Jost type, compass-star logo, source-seal, and hero components into a maintained component library so brand consistency survives future edits.", "Animation/asset governance: cinematic heroes and custom tarot/flat-lay art need an asset pipeline (compression, CDN, versioning) and a motion budget policy (reduced-motion, mobile fallbacks) enforced on every new page.", "Ongoing accessibility and performance regression testing in CI, given the heavy motion and low-contrast risk areas.", "Continuous CRO: run the standardized CTA, guarantee placement, and social-proof changes as measured experiments, and keep iterating rather than treating the copy pass as final.", "SEO monitoring post-launch: watch rankings, indexation, and redirect integrity for the high-value existing URLs.", "Security/compliance upkeep stays with the existing integrated stack (PCI, auth, age-gating) — the redesign layer must not become a shadow path around those controls."], "cost_effort": "As a lift-and-shift replacement the effort is very high and mostly invisible in this deliverable: the prototype is maybe 15–20% of a real platform (the presentation layer), and the missing 80%+ — telephony/per-minute billing, payments, presence/availability, accounts, CMS for 190+ profiles, SEO migration, analytics, compliance, localization — is exactly what already exists in production and would have to be rebuilt or re-integrated. That path is a multi-quarter, multi-team rebuild with real risk of taking the business offline. As what it should be — a design-system-and-CRO adoption reskinning the existing stack — the effort is moderate and high-leverage: extract tokens/components/hero patterns, re-template the current site's pages in the new look, rebind the advisor grid to live data, run accessibility/performance hardening, and A/B test the conversion changes. That is a design + front-end engineering effort measured in weeks-to-a-couple-months, riding on top of the backend that already works, with the expensive systems left untouched.", "worth_it": "Yes — the design system and conversion ideas are worth adopting and are the real asset here; a premium look is a legitimate competitive edge in a category that looks cheap. No — it is not worth adopting as a replacement site. Harvest the aesthetic, component library, hero concepts, and CRO copy; re-implement them on the existing production platform behind live data and compliant payment/auth flows; and validate the premium bet with an A/B test on first-paid-reading conversion. Do that and this prototype pays for itself. Swap it in wholesale and you trade a working 35-year revenue engine for a beautiful brochure."}, "personas": [{"name": "Heartbroken Hannah", "archetype": "The Raw Late-Night Seeker", "age": "34", "context": "Three weeks out from a painful breakup, awake at 1am wondering if he'll come back and terrified of being played.", "goal": "Someone to tell me the truth about him and me tonight, so I can either hope or finally let go and sleep.", "first_impression": "It doesn't look like the sad, blinking psychic sites I was bracing for. It's dim and beautiful, more like a candlelit spa than a hotline, and it made my shoulders drop a little. \"Answers you can trust\" landed on me before I even scrolled. The Love page line, \"The heart keeps its own counsel, and sometimes it will not tell you what it knows,\" actually made my eyes sting because that is exactly where I am right now.", "what_works": ["The Love page speaks to my exact situation without being cheesy: reunion timing, moving on, 'how to close a chapter without carrying it forever' is literally the sentence in my head", "'Clarity does not cool a feeling. It gives you somewhere to stand' reassured me this isn't just someone telling me what I want to hear", "The satisfaction guarantee and 'from $1/min' lowers the stakes so I'm not gambling money I don't have on a stranger", "35 years, 10M+ readings, only 2% of psychics accepted makes it feel vetted, not sketchy", "The calm luxury look makes me feel like a person seeking help, not a mark being milked"], "friction": ["I still don't know WHO I'd talk to at 1am tonight, or that someone is actually online right now, that uncertainty stops me cold", "The poetic voice is gorgeous but when I'm this raw I need one plain button that says 'talk to someone about my breakup now'", "Fear of manipulation is still there: what stops a psychic from stringing me along per-minute while I'm crying? I want to know how the money works before I start", "'$1/min' comforts me but I don't see the real price after the intro, and I'm scared of a $90 bill I didn't feel adding up", "Nothing tells me a reading tonight will actually make me feel better rather than worse, I need a hand to hold before I dial"], "would_convert": "Maybe", "tipping_point": "A live \"psychics available now\" strip showing a warm, high-rated love/relationship reader I could start with in one tap, plus a plain line telling me my first few minutes are $1/min and I can stop anytime, right next to the guarantee. Seeing a real face who's online right now would turn my crying into clicking.", "quote": "It finally feels like a place that would be gentle with me instead of cashing in on me, but at 1am I don't need poetry, I need to know someone's actually there right now and it won't quietly drain my account while I fall apart."}, {"name": "Grieving Grace", "archetype": "The Bereaved Seeker (skeptical, tender)", "age": "58", "context": "Retired teacher who lost her husband of 30 years last year and is quietly wondering if a medium could bring a sign or some peace.", "goal": "To find out, without being taken advantage of, whether a reading might give me one honest moment of connection or closure with my husband.", "first_impression": "My shoulders came down a little. It doesn't look like the cheap, flashing psychic-hotline pages I braced myself for. It's quiet and dignified, the deep violet and gold feel like a chapel more than a carnival, and the mediumship line stopped me cold: \"Grief does not end a relationship. It changes how you reach for it.\" Whoever wrote that has actually grieved, or listened closely to someone who has. That single sentence did more to earn my trust than all the numbers.", "what_works": ["The mediumship writing is gentle and honest instead of salesy: 'no theater here and no promises we cannot keep' is exactly the restraint I needed to hear", "\"never asking you to believe more than you feel\" tells me they won't push me past my own skepticism, which is the thing I was most afraid of", "The 35 years, 10M+ readings and 270K five-star reviews make it feel established and accountable, not a fly-by-night operation", "The 100% satisfaction guarantee, \"if your first reading isn't right, we'll make it right,\" lowers the stakes of trying", "The overall dignity of the design, cream serif type, calm cosmic imagery, signals they take this seriously and aren't out to spook or dazzle me"], "friction": ["\"For entertainment. 18+\" sitting right under such tender grief copy landed like a slap. It quietly says 'don't take this seriously,' and it makes me wonder if the beautiful words are just marketing after all", "\"$1/min\" reassures me at first, but I don't know what it costs after the first reading or how long a real session runs. I picture the meter running while I'm crying and I get anxious about being milked", "I don't see a single medium's face, name, or story specifically for grief and loss. I'd want to read reviews from other widows, not just a 4.9 average, before I trust one with my husband's memory", "The polish is almost too perfect, and part of me fears a place this beautifully packaged is very good at selling to vulnerable people, which is precisely what I promised myself I'd watch for", "I want to know HOW a medium is chosen for me and whether I can find someone who specializes in bereavement, not just click a gold button and be handed to whoever's online"], "would_convert": "Maybe", "tipping_point": "A named, grief-specialized medium I could see and read real bereavement reviews for, paired with clear, plain pricing (what a typical first reading actually costs, and a promise I control when it ends) so I never fear the meter is exploiting my tears, and softening or moving that \"for entertainment\" line away from the grief copy.", "quote": "\"The words made me cry in the good way, but then 'for entertainment' made me feel foolish for believing them. Show me a real person who's helped a widow like me, tell me plainly what it costs, and I'll pick up the phone.\""}, {"name": "Career-Crossroads Carla", "archetype": "Analytical decision-seeker at a career fork", "age": "41", "context": "Mid-level manager weighing a safe job against a risky startup offer, reads every review before spending a dollar.", "goal": "Get an outside, honest read on a high-stakes career decision that gives me clarity and the confidence to actually commit, without feeling scammed.", "first_impression": "This does not look like the cheap psychic sites I braced myself for. It reads like a serious, established brand — the deep violet and gold, the serif headlines, \"Answers you can trust.\" My guard dropped a notch. My first instinct was relief that it feels grown-up, followed immediately by my usual skepticism: pretty design is exactly how you dress up something soft, so I started hunting for substance.", "what_works": ["\"Answers you can trust\" as the H1 speaks directly to what I actually want — I don't want mysticism, I want direction I can rely on", "The specificity in the reviews sold me more than any design element: \"She told me to wait three weeks before making the call. She was right to the day\" and Priya's \"I was ready to quit my whole career... one honest question changed the decision\" — that is literally my situation", "Concrete social proof: 35 years, 10M+ readings, 270k five-star reviews, and especially \"only 2% of psychics accepted\" — the vetting angle matters to me because I distrust vagueness", "$1/min for new members plus the satisfaction guarantee lowers the cost of a test — I can try one reading for the price of a coffee", "The consultative framing (\"one honest question to sit with\" rather than fortune-telling) fits how I'd actually use this — as a thinking tool, not a prophecy"], "friction": ["The \"For insight and entertainment. 18+.\" disclaimer undercuts everything — if I'm making a real career decision, being told it's \"entertainment\" makes me question taking any of it seriously", "The guarantee is NOT money-back — it's account credit toward another psychic. That's a retention trap, not real risk reversal. I wanted my dollar back, not a nudge to spend more", "$1/min sounds great until I do the math: a real conversation is 20-30 minutes, and after the intro the regular rate is $8.99–$13.99/min. I can't see what a full session actually costs me before I commit", "270k five-star reviews and 4.9 with essentially no visible negatives reads as too clean — where are the 2- and 3-star ones? Curated perfection makes me trust it less, not more", "How do I pick the RIGHT psychic for a career question out of 190? I don't want love/pet/medium — I want someone credible on career and money, and I'm not sure how to filter to proven quality"], "would_convert": "Maybe", "tipping_point": "A clear path to the right advisor for MY exact question — a filter or short list of career/decision specialists with verified reviews specifically about work choices — paired with an honest, upfront cost for a typical 20-minute session and a genuine money-back (not credit-only) first reading. Drop the \"entertainment\" framing near that flow, and I'd put in the dollar.", "quote": "\"It finally looks trustworthy instead of tacky, and Priya's review could be my own diary — but tell me it's 'entertainment' and only give me store credit back, and you've just reminded me why I hesitate. Show me the right person for a career call and what it really costs, and I'm in.\""}, {"name": "Skeptical Sam", "archetype": "Curious Skeptic (never-user, dragged in by a friend's rave)", "age": "29", "context": "Software engineer, assumes psychics are entertainment/nonsense, poking around for fun after a friend wouldn't shut up about her reading.", "goal": "See if this is a low-risk, non-cringe way to try one reading for laughs without getting sucked into a subscription or feeling scammed.", "first_impression": "Honestly? Not what I expected. I braced for a flashing-neon \"YOUR DESTINY AWAITS\" carnival site and instead got something that looks like a perfume ad or a boutique hotel. The deep violet, the gold, the serif type, the drifting stars — it's genuinely well-made. My engineer brain clocked the polish immediately: this took real design work. It doesn't look like a scam, which is the first hurdle for me. \"Answers you can trust\" plus \"since 1989\" and the 4.9/270K-reviews block does the reassurance job. It reads premium and calm rather than desperate.", "what_works": ["The aesthetic disarms the cringe factor — I can browse this without feeling embarrassed, which is the #1 thing keeping me out of psychic sites", "Concrete, checkable social proof: 35 years, 10M+ readings, 270K 5-star reviews, 4.9 rating, 'only 2% accepted' — numbers I can respect even if I don't believe in the product", "'Satisfaction guaranteed / money back' right next to the CTA — that's exactly the risk-reversal my low-commitment brain needs to hear", "$1/min entry is a genuinely cheap on-ramp; a 5-minute goof costs me a coffee", "Media logos (USA Today, etc.) and 'Available now' status on real psychics make it feel like a legit operating marketplace, not a fake storefront", "Phone/chat/video options with 'keep the transcript' — chat feels lower-stakes than getting on a phone call with a stranger, which I'd never do"], "friction": ["No truly free, zero-commitment on-ramp. '$1/min' still means I have to create an account and put in a credit card before anything happens — that's a wall for someone just here for fun", "The meter is scary. $1/min sounds cheap until I imagine a call running long. I have no sense of what a typical reading costs total, and 'per minute' triggers my 'they're incentivized to stall' instinct", "'Satisfied or your money back' is vague — what actually qualifies? Do I dispute it? Is it a fight? Guarantees that easy usually have fine print", "How-it-works never explains the actual billing mechanics — signup, card, cancellation, how the meter starts/stops. As an engineer I want the plumbing, and its absence reads as 'don't look too closely'", "The premium mystical framing ('a Guide is Summoned,' 'the cosmos flowing between them') is beautiful but still fundamentally asks me to buy that someone has a 'gift.' Nothing here addresses the skeptic directly or gives me a playful, no-belief-required way in", "'For entertainment. 18+.' is honest but also quietly admits the whole thing, which paradoxically makes me less willing to pay real money for it"], "would_convert": "Maybe", "tipping_point": "A genuinely free, no-card first taste — like \"your first 3 minutes free\" or a free single-question chat — so I could try it once for zero risk and zero commitment. Pair that with a clear cap or estimated total (\"most first readings run $15-25\") so the meter stops feeling like a trap, and I'd probably do it on a lark.", "quote": "\"Okay, this is way classier than I expected — but you still want my credit card before I've even seen if this is fun. Give me three free minutes and I might actually do it as a joke; make me commit a card to a per-minute meter and I'm closing the tab.\""}, {"name": "Spiritual Sofia", "archetype": "The Discerning Practitioner", "age": "47", "context": "Yoga instructor who reads her own tarot and tracks the moon; she's not shopping for magic, she's testing whether these people actually have any.", "goal": "Find a genuinely gifted reader for a real question about a relationship crossroads — someone with depth, not a call-center psychic reading off a script.", "first_impression": "My guard went up when I saw \"psychicsource.com,\" because those sites are usually neon purple and desperate. This isn't. It breathes. The deep indigo, the champagne gold, the Cormorant serif, the quiet drifting stars — it reads like a heritage house, not a hotline. And then the tarot copy actually stopped me: \"Tarot does not predict so much as reflect. It gives shape to what you already sense and cannot yet say.\" That is a real sentence written by someone who has actually sat with the cards. That earned a second look I do not usually give these places.", "what_works": ["The tarot language is authentic, not cliche — \"reflect, not predict\" and \"the moment the cards stop being pictures and become yours\" is how a real practitioner talks", "The restraint of the aesthetic: cosmic without being costume-y, luxurious without being cold — it treats the practice as sacred rather than a gimmick", "\"Only 2% of psychics accepted\" and \"rigorously vetted\" speaks directly to my fear of getting a fake — curation is the thing I actually care about", "The 35 years / 10M readings / 270K reviews scaffolding makes it feel like an institution, which is reassuring for something this intimate", "Framing readings as \"The Ritual\" and naming the arc Seeker / Oracle / Insight — that's a considered narrative, and it flatters my intelligence instead of talking down to me"], "friction": ["\"For entertainment only. 18+\" at the bottom is a cold bucket of water — it quietly admits none of this is real, which undercuts every sincere word above it and is exactly the tell I'm scanning for", "\"New members from $1/min\" reads like a bait hook; the beauty of the design and the discount-hotline offer are speaking two different languages, and the mismatch makes me suspicious", "I can feel the polish, but I haven't met a single human yet — I want a specific reader's face, voice, actual words, a real review with a name, before I trust the curation claim", "\"Rigorously vetted\" and \"only 2% accepted\" are asserted, not shown — as a practitioner I want to know HOW they vet gift, not just that they do", "The cosmic-luxury wrapper is gorgeous but risks feeling like set-dressing; if the advisor page underneath is generic stock-photo psychics, the whole spell breaks instantly"], "would_convert": "Maybe", "tipping_point": "Let me actually meet a psychic before I pay — a real profile with her own words about how she works, her specialty, and a few named, specific reviews from real seekers. If I can find one woman on the advisors page whose language feels as authentic as the tarot copy, and book HER for that $1/min first read, I'm in. I convert on a person, not on the brand.", "quote": "\"It's the first psychic site that didn't make me cringe — but 'for entertainment only' at the bottom is exactly the thing that makes me hesitate. Show me a real reader whose words ring true, and I'll book her tonight.\""}, {"name": "Anxious Dana", "archetype": "The Overwhelmed Decision-Seeker", "age": "38", "context": "A nurse deciding whether to uproot her whole life and move across the country for her partner, and she just wants someone to help her think it through without judging her.", "goal": "Get a calm, honest second opinion about a huge relocation-for-love decision and feel genuinely heard rather than sold to.", "first_impression": "My shoulders actually dropped a little. I expected a flashing, cheap-looking psychic hotline and instead this feels quiet and grown-up, like walking into a candlelit room instead of a casino. \"Answers you can trust\" spoke straight to the knot in my stomach, and the whole thing feels calm rather than desperate for my money.", "what_works": ["\"Answers you can trust\" as the headline lands right where my anxiety lives; that is exactly the thing I am missing right now", "The Love & Relationships page felt like it was written by someone who understands me: \"When feelings run high, clarity runs thin\" is literally my last three weeks", "The line \"The gift is not to tell you what you want to hear. It is to tell you what is real, gently enough that you can hold it\" made me trust that I would not be flattered or manipulated", "Non-judgment is stated out loud, psychics who have \"sat with every shape of love\" - that matters because I am a little embarrassed to be asking a psychic at all", "The satisfaction guarantee (\"If your first reading isn't right, we'll make it right\") plus $1/min makes trying it feel low-stakes for someone watching her money", "35 years, 10M+ readings, 270,000 five-star reviews - the numbers quiet the part of me that worries this is a scam", "The calm, premium look itself is reassuring; it signals these people take this seriously and are not just farming lonely women"], "friction": ["I want to pick a person, not a service. Before I pay I need to see WHO I would talk to - a warm face, a bio, someone who specializes in relationships and life transitions. The homepage sells the brand but does not hand me a specific human to trust", "\"$1/min\" reassures and worries me at once - my real fear is the meter running while I am emotional and rambling. How long does a reading actually take? Could this quietly become $60 before I know it? I want honesty about typical cost, not just the per-minute hook", "\"Rigorously vetted\" and \"fewer than 1 in 20 accepted\" is nice but vague - vetted for what? I want to know they are kind and grounded, not just \"gifted\"", "Part of me still feels silly, like a smart nurse should not need a psychic to make a life decision. Nothing on the page fully gives me permission to be here without that flicker of shame", "It is beautiful but I have a tiny worry that pretty packaging means premium pricing once the $1 intro runs out ($8.75-$13.99/min in the crossed-out prices caught my eye)"], "would_convert": "Maybe", "tipping_point": "Let me browse the psychics and land on a warm, specific person - a real photo, a bio that says they specialize in love and big life decisions, strong reviews from people in situations like mine - and pair that with a plain-English note on what a first reading actually costs and how long it usually runs. Seeing a human I trust, backed by the guarantee, is what turns my \"maybe\" into clicking Get Your Reading.", "quote": "I don't need someone to tell me to move or stay - I need someone kind to help me hear myself think, and this is the first psychic site that didn't make me feel foolish for wanting that."}, {"name": "Loyal Rosa", "archetype": "The Long-Time Regular (loyalty-first, change-avery)", "age": "62", "context": "Small-business owner, 15 years with this service and two readers I call by extension; I don't want a redesign hiding what I use or touching my price.", "goal": "Get to my two trusted psychics fast, confirm my member rate and reward points didn't change, and keep my 24/7 phone access.", "first_impression": "It's beautiful, honestly prettier than I expected, but my very first feeling was a little jolt of worry: fancy usually means they moved my stuff and changed the prices. My second thought was relief the toll-free number is still right up top in the header.", "what_works": ["The phone number +1.800.965.3049 is in the header and footer, so I know I can still just call the way I always do", "There's a 'Find By Name or Extension' search on the psychics page, that's the first thing I look for and it's exactly how I reach my regulars", "Each psychic shows a live status ('Available now', 'In a reading', 'Away - leave a message') so I can see if my reader is on before I dial", "The rewards page kept a real loyalty program with 'priority matching to your favorites' and points that redeem for minutes, and it says points build faster with repeat psychics, which is me", "24/7 access is stated plainly, that's non-negotiable for me and they kept it"], "friction": ["The big '$1/min' offer everywhere is for NEW members - nowhere does it reassure a 15-year customer that MY rate is unchanged, so I'm left worried they raised my price", "The rewards tiers got renamed to Seeker/Devotee/Luminary with 'starlight points' - I have no idea what happened to my existing status and point balance, or whether it carried over", "'Membership Rewards' is only a tiny footer link on the homepage - my whole reason for staying is buried", "They changed 'advisors' to 'psychics' - small thing, but it makes me wonder what else quietly changed, like whether my saved favorites and extensions still work", "All the drifting stars and spinning cards are lovely but I worry the site's slower and busier than the plain one I know how to use"], "would_convert": "Maybe", "tipping_point": "Seeing my two regulars still listed under their same extensions, plus one clear line for existing members saying my rate and my accumulated reward points carried over unchanged - then I'd call the same as always.", "quote": "It's gorgeous, but I don't need gorgeous - I need to know my two ladies are still one call away and nobody touched my rate or my points."}, {"name": "Budget Bella", "archetype": "Anxious Budget Seeker", "age": "26", "context": "Barista on a tight budget, curious about a first reading but terrified of a surprise bill.", "goal": "Try one reading about my relationship without accidentally spending money I don't have.", "first_impression": "Honestly? It's gorgeous. It doesn't look like the sketchy neon psychic sites I expected — it feels expensive, calm, and legit, like a real 35-year-old company and not a scam. The deep purple and gold, the star logo, the \"Answers you can trust\" line — I actually trusted it more instantly. But part of me got nervous because \"luxury\" and \"cheap\" don't usually go together, so my first thought was \"okay this looks pretty, but is this going to be affordable for someone like me?\"", "what_works": ["The $1/min for new members is right there under the button — that's the ONLY reason I didn't close the tab, that's the whole thing for me", "'Satisfaction guaranteed' and 'if your first reading isn't right, we'll make it right' near the CTA calms the money-back fear a little", "The social proof (10M+ readings, 270K five-star reviews, 4.9, since 1989) makes it feel safe and real, not a scam that'll steal my card", "It looks premium and trustworthy instead of cheap and predatory, which honestly matters for something this personal", "One clear button everywhere — 'Get Your Reading' — I never felt lost about what to click"], "friction": ["Nowhere does it tell me how MANY minutes I get at $1/min — is it 3 minutes? 10? 20? That's the single scariest gap for me", "No total cost shown. $1/min sounds cheap but the psychics list $9.99/min as the real rate, so what happens when my intro minutes run out mid-sentence? Do I get slammed at $9.99 without warning?", "I can't find how billing actually works or how I stop a reading before it runs up a bill — no 'you control it, ends when you say' reassurance", "'From $1/min' — the word 'from' makes me suspicious it's more for the psychic I actually want", "No mention of adding a set amount or a hard spending cap, which is exactly what a broke person needs to feel safe", "The tiny '18+ · for entertainment' fine print reminded me this can get expensive fast if I'm not careful"], "would_convert": "Maybe", "tipping_point": "One plain line near the button that says exactly how many minutes I get at $1 and that I set a spending limit up front and it stops automatically — like \"Your first 10 minutes are $1/min, set your budget, and it ends when your time's up. No surprise charges.\" Give me a guaranteed stop point and a known total, and I'd put my card in tonight.", "quote": "It's the prettiest psychic site I've ever seen and the $1 a minute almost got me — but nobody told me how many minutes that buys or how I stop before it eats my rent, so I froze with my finger over the button."}, {"name": "Night-Owl Wendy", "archetype": "The 2am Reassurance-Seeker (impatient, immediacy-first)", "age": "45", "context": "Freelancer with insomnia whose anxieties spike in the small hours; she wants to talk to a real person right now, tonight.", "goal": "Get on the phone or into a chat with an available psychic within the next couple of minutes to calm a 2am worry — not read a manifesto.", "first_impression": "It's beautiful in a way psychic sites never are — calm, deep violet, gold, quiet. My shoulders actually dropped a little. But my second thought was: pretty is nice, but is anyone actually awake right now, and how fast can I reach them? The elegance almost reads slow, like it wants me to linger when I want to connect.", "what_works": ["The 1-800 number sitting right in the header — that's the single most reassuring thing on the page for someone like me; I can bypass everything and just call.", "'Psychics available now · connect 24/7' speaks directly to my 2am problem, and the '● Available now' green dots next to psychics make it feel like real people are actually online.", "Phone AND chat AND video all offered — I want options depending on whether I feel like talking or typing at this hour.", "'New members from $1/min · Satisfaction guaranteed' lowers the stakes; if the read is bad I'm not out much, and the guarantee quiets the 'is this a scam' voice.", "The whole thing feels trustworthy and premium instead of the usual cheap flashing-neon psychic sites — the calm actually helps my anxiety."], "friction": ["Nowhere does it tell me the wait time or how many taps until I'm actually talking to someone — 'insight begins the moment you dare to ask' is poetry, not a connect button, and poetry annoys me at 2am.", "'Get Your Reading' implies a sign-up / new-member flow before I reach a person. If I have to create an account, enter a card, and get 'matched' first, I may bail — I want to click a live psychic and go.", "The 3-step 'You Ask → Matching → Insight' is conceptual, not operational; I still don't know if 'matching' is instant or a queue.", "I can't tell from the CTA whether clicking calls someone immediately or drops me into a browse-and-decide maze; the immediacy is asserted but not demonstrated.", "Slightly worried the luxury polish means luxury pricing once the intro $1/min runs out, and I don't see the real per-minute rate up front."], "would_convert": "Maybe", "tipping_point": "A dead-simple 'Talk to a psychic now' path that shows me who's online this second and gets me on the phone/chat in one or two taps with a visible wait time ('connect in under 60 seconds') — proof of immediacy, not just the promise of it.", "quote": "\"It's the prettiest psychic site I've ever seen and I actually trust it — now just let me tap one button and talk to somebody before I lose my nerve at 2am.\""}, {"name": "Gift-Giver Greg", "archetype": "The Practical Gift-Giver", "age": "52", "context": "An accountant with zero interest in psychics himself, trying to buy something meaningful for his spiritually-inclined sister.", "goal": "Buy a psychic reading as a gift that feels legitimate and premium (not embarrassing), and hand it over easily.", "first_impression": "Honestly, relief. My gut expectation of a psychic website was flashing neon, crystal-ball clip art, and something that would make me embarrassed to put my sister's name on it. This looks like a real brand — the deep violet, the gold, the serif type, \"trusted since 1989.\" It reads more like a boutique wellness or spa site than a fortune-teller hotline. That instantly makes it feel giftable and less like I'm getting scammed.", "what_works": ["The premium look does the heavy lifting — it kills the embarrassment factor. I could show this to my sister without cringing.", "Hard trust numbers I can respect as a numbers guy: 10M+ readings, 270K five-star reviews, 4.9 rating, 35 years, only ~2% of psychics accepted. That vetting stat matters to me.", "The satisfaction guarantee near the buttons — risk reversal is exactly what a cautious buyer wants to see.", "'Answers you can trust' plus phone/chat/video options — clear, benefit-led, not mystical word-salad.", "Recognizable media logos (USA Today, Lifetime, FOX) — cheap credibility, but it works on me."], "friction": ["The dealbreaker: there is no gift card or 'buy as a gift' option anywhere. My entire reason for being here isn't served. I don't want an account tied to MY phone and MY card — I want to give HER a reading.", "The whole flow assumes I'm the seeker. It wants me to bring my question and connect right now. That's not my use case at all.", "'$1/min' is a per-minute meter, which for a gift is awkward — how do I gift 'minutes'? I'd want a fixed-dollar gift ('a $50 reading') I can hand over, not a running taxi meter my sister has to watch.", "No pricing certainty for a gift. As an accountant I want to know the total I'm spending, not a variable rate between $1 and $13.99/min.", "I have to guess how she'd even redeem it. No 'give the gift of guidance' explainer, no gift email/print option, no code."], "would_convert": "No", "tipping_point": "A clear 'Give a Reading' / gift-card path with fixed-dollar amounts, a printable or emailable gift with a redemption code, and a one-line 'here's how she redeems it' — so I can buy a set amount, put her name on it, and be done without linking it to my own account or a ticking meter.", "quote": "This finally looks classy enough to actually give my sister — but there's nowhere to buy it AS a gift, and I'm not signing up with my own card and a per-minute meter for a present."}]};
